<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12056c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12056c">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12056c"> 56(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> man-at-arms, page, coutilier / 2 archer, servant</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Or, d&apos;apr&egrave;s les r&egrave;gles de l&apos;organisation des arm&eacute;es anglaises en France, au cours du quinzi&egrave;me si&egrave;cle, on peut dire qu&apos;en principe la proportion des archers par rapport aux hommes d&apos;armes &eacute;tait de 3 pour 1. Chaque homme d&apos;armes &eacute;tait escort&eacute; d&apos;un page et d&apos;un coutilier; chaque couple d&apos;archers avait un servant. Si donc, &agrave; une date d&eacute;termin&eacute;e, il est dit qu&apos;il y avait 20 hommes d&apos;armes &agrave; Tombelaine, il faut en conclure qu&apos;il y avait: Hommes d&apos;armes. 20 / Archers. 60 / Pages 20 / Coutiliers 20 / Servants 30 / Au total une garnison de 150 hommes. <br><font color="green">[So, according to the rules of the organisation of English armies in France during the fifteenth century we can say that normally the proportion of archers to armed men was three to one. Every armed man was accompanied by a page and a courtier; two archers had one servant. So when at a certain date it is claimed that 20 armed men were at Tombelaine, that means the following: Armed men 20 / Archers 60 / Pages 20 / Courtiers 20 / Servants 30 / A total garrison of &hellip; 150 men.]</font> <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="SMIN" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SMIN"><cite title="source">Le Mont Saint-Michel Inconnu</cite></a> (1912) 114-5</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
